metadata.name: COMPUTERS #2
metadata.description:
Generative animated painting made from pixel array computations and classic noise algorithms.

COMPUTERS is a meditation on the aesthetics of computing in all of its forms. It recalls the types of computation required to build temples, write complex texts, weave detailed textiles, and program computer games. Pixels have always existed in some form or another, before and after the screen. Every iteration of COMPUTERS suggests that computation is both contemporary and ancient.

Press 'p' or click to pause the animation.
Press 's' to capture a single frame.
Made with P5.js and GLSL. By @galoandstuff.

metadata.name: Scribble Kittens #20
metadata.description: Scribble Kittens float through their existence mostly unnoticed, they are created seemingly at random in darkened corners while nobody is watching. The most keen-eyed individuals will often find them in the early morning, especially those individuals who wear their socks to bed.

metadata.name: Caustic Obstacles #106
metadata.description:
An exploration of light transport and pathtracing in 2D.

In collaboration with TENDER.

Press "s" to save a screenshot. Caustic Obstacles uses progressive monte carlo rendering, meaning that at first the image will appear noisy, but over time it will become smoother. It may take up to several minutes for the noise to become unnoticeable (or longer, if you specify a very high resolution). The piece is never officially "done" rendering, but instead becomes asymptotically smoother with time - take your screenshots whenever you feel it's smooth enough!

Use the url "width" parameter to change the resolution of the piece, e.g. "/?width=2160". Every edition is rendered in a 5x7 aspect ratio, and the height will be determined automatically based on the width specified. This means that the height will be determined with the formula width * 7 / 5, rounded up. By default the width is 1080, which results in a height of 1512, while a width of, for example, 2160, would result in a height of 3024.



–––––––
TENDER x ella
December 2023  
Caustic Obstacles is a generative art series created by Ella Hoeppner in collaboration with Adam Berninger of Tender.
–––––––

metadata.name: Triangular Dreams #2
metadata.description:
Delaunay triangulation is a good old resource in the generative toolbox. In this work I’ve tried to give it a new twist, combining it with different methods to place points in space, and filling each triangle with lines that go from one corner to the opposite side. The goal is to generate a wide range of semi-abstract scenes, that can sometimes be reminiscent of the work of Paul Klee, Lyonel Feininger or other Bauhaus members.

Controls:
[c] to switch between 3 color modes: color mixes, color zones and monochrome
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to save a screen capture
[2] to [9] to generate and save a hi-res image at 2x, 3x, … your viewport size

This work will adapt nicely to any screen format.
No palettes have been used, it is all random colors within a certain hue and saturation range.
Made with p5.js and d3.js

metadata.name: Hatch Field 001 #92
metadata.description:
Genesis p5js drawing on fx(hash). Experimenting with translating recent work in done in Grasshopper exploring hatch patterns to p5.js. By Andrew Kudless / Matsys @matsysdesign
There are four feature groups:
- Base Hue: Red, Orange, Yellow, Spring Green, Green, Ocean Green, Cyan, Sky Blue, Blue, Purple, Magenta, and Crimson. Each has the same random chance of being the base color (12%).
- Hue Range: Narrow (14%), Wide (51%), and Infinite(34%)
- Lineweight: Thin (75%), Medium (10%), Thick (10%), Extra Thick (5%)
-Fray: Loose (90%), Tight (10%)

metadata.name: reflection 2 #7
metadata.description:
A thorough reworking of the "reflection" code to produce an entirely different result. Rather than the hard angles of a cityscape, moderate changes (and much experimentation) produce a hill by a lake at sunrise. 

It is interesting to me how the human brain wants to find patterns it is familiar with in an essentially random pile of squares. I feel that this is a feature, rather than a bug, of the human psyche. It certainly makes abstract art viable. 

Created, as always, in p5.js

metadata.name: anomalia.12 #66
metadata.description:
Each one of the creations are movements in search of irregularity. Sequential modulation of shapes with the oscillator causes a sense of depth. With the help of noise and voronoi, it was possible to simulate a kind of dance between the shapes. Made with Hydra library.

Full screen will provide you a better view of the elements.

humanized
experiment

São Paulo, Brasil. 25/Janeiro/2022

metadata.name: Ataraxis #431
metadata.description:
Ataraxis (or a broken volume renderer) is an exploration in balancing discomfort and calm. The piece generates spaces on the fly that are designed to elicit strange and uncomfortable feelings - like a desolate, alien dreamscape - claustrophobic, surreal, not quite real yet strangely recognisable. But the idea is that while these spaces feel uncomfortable, they're also strangely, antilogically calming. The idea is to elicit a sanguine emotion, to make the viewer feel calm in a strange place, and to lead them somewhere else.

This work is the culmination of many years of work researching volumetric rendering techniques. This token uses a raymarching technique that is intentionally broken in various ways.

Controls:
Double-click to download
&w=X&h=y to change the size of the piece
&dpr=x to change the resolution of the pice - higher resolutions will result in slightly different artworks as the browser attempts to compensate for the overlarge canvas
&fullscreen=true to change the token to display the full size of your browser. This may impact the rendering of the token, so use with caution
